Coronavirus guidance is being updated.
Read what you can and cannot do

Bahamas has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Bahamas, see Return to the UK
On 17 March 2020, the Governor General declared a state of public emergency in The Bahamas. On 23 March 2020, the Prime Minister of the Bahamas announced further emergency measures to combat the spread of COVID-19 see full measures.
On 27 April the state of public emergency was extended until 30 May 2020. A 24 hour curfew limiting movement and shopping is in place every day with a total lockdown (with all stores closed and no travel allowed) during weekends through to 30 May 2020. The last commercial flight to Europe was on 22 March; there are severely limited flights to the US subject to cancellation and change; and future flights are not guaranteed. See Return to the UK
Local measures
Emergency measures are in place including a national 24 hour curfew from Monday to Friday until 30 May. Many businesses have closed, but those that provide essential services (including grocery stores) continue with restricted hours; as well as stores that provide online or telephone ordering with delivery or curbside pick-up. Social distancing and wearing facemasks is obligatory for everyone leaving their own property.
Additionally there are periods of total lock down at weekends during May (with all stores closed and a ban on movement for non-essential personnel) Doctor’s offices, hospitals and medical facilities remain open. Many hotels have closed. More details are available at the website of the Office of the Prime Minister of the Bahamas.
The Bahamas have closed all airports and ports to incoming flights and vessels (including domestic inter-island travel). Outbound flights are allowed and are operating to the USA but are severely disrupted. No direct commercial flights to Europe have been possible since 22 March due to previously announced restrictions and British Airways are suspending services until 1 July.
Several other airlines and hotels have announced they will not operate until the restrictions are relaxed. Commercial international flight departures are severely limited and future flights are not guaranteed. These restrictions also extend to maritime traffic; private vessels; and cruise ships which are not allowed to disembark passengers or crew. They will also not be allowed to restock or refuel during weekend lock down periods, see Return to the UK
Travellers should contact their airlines, travel agents and tour operators. For information on how to return to the UK from The Bahamas, see Return to the UK.
If you’re in The Bahamas and concerned that you may have contracted coronavirus the Ministry of Health 24 hour call centre is (+ 1) (242) 502 7382. The Bahamas government also has the following call centres: 511 – for health related queries; 411 – for general questions on the restrictions; 911 – for emergency services.
If you’re concerned about your immigration status (e.g. overstaying a visa) due to the emergency restrictions the Department of Immigration is 225 5337 or immigration@bahamas.gov.bs. The Department of Immigration has also published guidance on how to apply for an electronic extension to stay. Details are available on their website
If you require a visitor visa, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs has an electronic visa application process. The official website is: https://mofa.gov.bs/obtaining-official-documents/visitors-visa/. Please email mofaconsular@bahamas.gov.bs for more information on visa processing fees and turn around times.
Further Information
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
